  "Prerequisites": "A basic familiarity with research methods and a general interest in how artificial intelligence tools are being used in academic or scientific settings is all that is required to begin this course.",
  "Learning objectives": "By the end of this course, you will be able to identify the key risks associated with AI-assisted research analysis and explain how fabricated or incorrect AI outputs can compromise scientific integrity. You will also apply practical strategies to critically evaluate AI-generated content and recognise the ethical responsibilities researchers hold when incorporating AI tools into their work.",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "lesson title": "AI in Research and Scientific Integrity",
      "order": 1,
      "Description": "This lesson introduces learners to the growing role of artificial intelligence in research and explores the important risks that come with relying on AI-assisted analysis. You will learn how AI tools can sometimes produce fabricated references, inaccurate data summaries, or misleading conclusions that appear convincing on the surface. We will look at real-world examples of how these errors can compromise scientific integrity and damage trust in published research. By the end of this lesson, you will have a clearer understanding of how to use AI tools responsibly, apply critical thinking when reviewing AI-generated outputs, and recognise when human oversight is essential. This lesson is designed for beginners and requires no prior technical knowledge, making it accessible to anyone involved in or curious about the research process.",
      "status": "draft",
